ralism, however, has been the status of scientific knowledge itself, which seems, at first glance, to be something that transcends and is therefore impossible to conceptualize within scientific naturalism itself. In Articulating the World, Joseph Rouse argues that the most pressing challenge for advocates of naturalism today is precisely this: to understand how to make sense of a scientific conception of nature as itself part of nature, scientifically understood. Drawing upon recent developments in evolutionary biology and the philosophy of science, Rouse defends naturalism in response to this challenge by revising both how we understand our scientific conception of the world and how we situate ourselves within it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aComprehension (Theory of knowledge) 0aComprehension (Theory of knowledge). 0aConcepts. 0aNaturalism. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  ascience, scientific, scientist, conceptual, concepts, understanding, philosophy, philosopher, philosophical, naturalist, naturalism, modern, contemporary, supernatural, transcendental, transcendent, nature, religious, faith, belief, paradox, knowledge, self, evolution, evolutionary, biology, biologist, interdisciplinary, theory, theoretical, academic, scholarly, research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022629367740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226293707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226293707/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles